00:00:41.260 --> 00:00:44.510
So last day, we were talking
about doping of

00:00:44.510 --> 00:00:48.790
semiconductors, and I want
to finish up that unit.

00:00:48.790 --> 00:00:52.370
Just to refresh your memory,
we looked at how we could

00:00:52.370 --> 00:00:55.850
change the behavior of the
semiconductor by introducing

00:00:55.850 --> 00:01:00.000
impurity atoms. And when the
behavior of the semiconductor

00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.300
is dominated by the impurity
atoms, we term

00:01:04.300 --> 00:01:05.750
that behavior extrinsic.

00:01:05.750 --> 00:01:08.080
In other words, it's not the
behavior of silicon itself,

00:01:08.080 --> 00:01:10.880
but it's the behavior of silicon
as determined by the

00:01:10.880 --> 00:01:13.750
presence of some dopant atom.

00:01:13.750 --> 00:01:16.880
And we looked at the special
case of doping with a

00:01:16.880 --> 00:01:18.530
supervalent impurity.

00:01:18.530 --> 00:01:21.630
And here's the energy level
diagram for that situation,

00:01:21.630 --> 00:01:24.590
where we've got the valence
band down here, we've got

00:01:24.590 --> 00:01:27.720
conduction band up here,
separated by an energy gap.

00:01:27.720 --> 00:01:31.370
That's all characteristic of
plain vanilla silicon.

00:01:31.370 --> 00:01:36.170
But then when we dope with the
supervalent impurity, there is

00:01:36.170 --> 00:01:37.800
an extra electron.

00:01:37.800 --> 00:01:42.900
And that is put into a donor
level that lies just a tiny

00:01:42.900 --> 00:01:45.850
bit below the bottom of
the conduction band.

00:01:45.850 --> 00:01:49.750
And then, thanks to thermal
excitation, which gives us an

00:01:49.750 --> 00:01:54.810
average energy of about 1/40 of
an electron bolt, we get,

00:01:54.810 --> 00:02:00.780
for all intents and purposes,
100% excitation of the

00:02:00.780 --> 00:02:04.650
electronics that sit in the
donor level, excitation up

00:02:04.650 --> 00:02:06.340
into the conduction band.

00:02:06.340 --> 00:02:09.450
And this is what electrical
engineers term ionization.

00:02:09.450 --> 00:02:13.310
And I also reminded you last
day that this is the donor

00:02:13.310 --> 00:02:20.210
level, and for each donor atom,
there sits a donor level

00:02:20.210 --> 00:02:23.570
at the same value of energy,
but these are so far apart

00:02:23.570 --> 00:02:27.150
point, owing to the dilution,
the dilute concentration of

00:02:27.150 --> 00:02:30.900
the impurity, that we
don't violate the

00:02:30.900 --> 00:02:32.610
Pauli Exclusion Principle.

00:02:32.610 --> 00:02:35.590
So these are all sitting at the
same level and that's why

00:02:35.590 --> 00:02:38.540
they've given temperature
promotes all of them up into

00:02:38.540 --> 00:02:41.830
the conduction band, where
they are mobile.

00:02:41.830 --> 00:02:48.410
And then, just to complete the
review, we call this n-type

00:02:48.410 --> 00:02:52.690
because, thanks to doping, we
generate electrons in the

00:02:52.690 --> 00:02:56.230
conduction band, and electrons
are negative.

00:02:56.230 --> 00:02:59.220
Supervalent doping
gives us n-type.

00:02:59.220 --> 00:03:03.080
Then the total number of
electrons in the conduction

00:03:03.080 --> 00:03:06.440
band is the sum of those that
would have been generated by

00:03:06.440 --> 00:03:08.530
plain old thermal excitation.

00:03:08.530 --> 00:03:11.620
Thermal excitation operates
all the time.

00:03:11.620 --> 00:03:17.500
So with thermal excitation,
recall, we promote from the

00:03:17.500 --> 00:03:20.160
valence band up into the
conduction band.

00:03:20.160 --> 00:03:24.080
So we break one of these bonds,
shoot an electron up

00:03:24.080 --> 00:03:26.280
here, and leave a hole behind.

00:03:26.280 --> 00:03:28.100
So this generates the pair.

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:30.870
Hole in the valence band,
and electron in

00:03:30.870 --> 00:03:32.320
the conduction band.

00:03:32.320 --> 00:03:36.410
That's always operative, but
owing to the energies

00:03:36.410 --> 00:03:40.650
involved, the band gap is on
the order of one electron

00:03:40.650 --> 00:03:46.420
volt, whereas the donor level
sits only about 1/50 of an

00:03:46.420 --> 00:03:48.470
electron volt below the
conduction band.

00:03:48.470 --> 00:03:52.820
So we get very, very little
promotion at room temperature.

00:03:52.820 --> 00:03:55.680
And in fact, it's something like
10 to the minus 19 is the

00:03:55.680 --> 00:03:59.110
fraction of promotion, and if
you say roughly 10 to the

00:03:59.110 --> 00:04:01.260
twenty-third per cubic
centimeter, that means you've

00:04:01.260 --> 00:04:05.650
got about 10 to the fourth
electrons per cubic centimeter

00:04:05.650 --> 00:04:08.680
due to this thermal excitation
from the valence band to the

00:04:08.680 --> 00:04:10.120
conduction band.

00:04:10.120 --> 00:04:12.880
Normally, when you dope a
semiconductor, you dope it

00:04:12.880 --> 00:04:15.080
around parts per
million level.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:18.110
And parts per million, that's
10 to the minus 6.

00:04:18.110 --> 00:04:20.680
If you take 10 to the minus 6
times 10 to the 23, you get

00:04:20.680 --> 00:04:21.960
about 10 of the 17.

00:04:21.960 --> 00:04:25.600
Now you can see, 10 of the 17
is vastly larger than 10 of

00:04:25.600 --> 00:04:26.360
the fourth.

00:04:26.360 --> 00:04:29.180
So for all intents and purposes,
once you've doped

00:04:29.180 --> 00:04:32.780
something, this contribution is
essentially 0, and so the

00:04:32.780 --> 00:04:35.140
electron population, the
conduction band, is that

00:04:35.140 --> 00:04:38.070
dictated by the impurity atoms,
which is why we say

00:04:38.070 --> 00:04:40.130
that this is exhibiting
extrinsic behavior.

00:04:40.130 --> 00:04:43.850
The intrinsic properties
are not

00:04:43.850 --> 00:04:46.135
visible, they're not palpable.

00:04:46.135 --> 00:04:47.610
They're immeasurable.

00:04:47.610 --> 00:04:51.180
So intrinsic is substantially
less than extrinsic.

00:04:51.180 --> 00:04:54.070
Now, the last thing I wanted
to do for you before we say

00:04:54.070 --> 00:04:57.030
goodbye to this fascinating
topic, which lays the

00:04:57.030 --> 00:04:59.730
groundwork for everything that
we know in the modern

00:04:59.730 --> 00:05:04.790
electronic era, parenthetically,
is to look at

00:05:04.790 --> 00:05:06.250
the other type of doping.

00:05:06.250 --> 00:05:08.810
I've showed you how to make
an n-type semiconductor.

00:05:08.810 --> 00:05:11.100
How do we make a p-type
semiconductor?

00:05:11.100 --> 00:05:13.930
So in that case, what
we can do is dope

00:05:13.930 --> 00:05:15.560
with a subvalent impurity.

00:05:20.490 --> 00:05:21.860
What do I mean by subvalent?

00:05:21.860 --> 00:05:26.770
Well, the valency of silicon
is 4, so I want

00:05:26.770 --> 00:05:28.020
something less than 4.

00:05:28.020 --> 00:05:32.770
So a good example is
boron into silicon.

00:05:35.290 --> 00:05:39.640
So boron is group 13, or 3, all
right, if you look on your

00:05:39.640 --> 00:05:40.600
periodic table.

00:05:40.600 --> 00:05:43.190
And silicon is group
14, according

00:05:43.190 --> 00:05:45.220
to the IUPAC notation.

00:05:45.220 --> 00:05:49.900
So let's go back and take a look
at how that might appear.

00:05:49.900 --> 00:05:52.440
So I'm going to draw the
silicon crystal.

00:05:52.440 --> 00:05:55.380
Remember, this is going into a
single crystal of silicon.

00:05:55.380 --> 00:05:59.650
So silicon is sp 3 hybridized,
and we have silicons

00:05:59.650 --> 00:06:01.660
everywhere in the structure.

00:06:01.660 --> 00:06:03.560
So we're going to
put silicons.

00:06:03.560 --> 00:06:06.150
And I'm trying to show
sp 3 hybridization.

00:06:06.150 --> 00:06:10.680
So this is 3 legs each in the
plane, then you've got 109

00:06:10.680 --> 00:06:11.340
degrees here.

00:06:11.340 --> 00:06:13.020
So that's silicon, and so on.

00:06:13.020 --> 00:06:15.450
I get the three of them
just to complete

00:06:15.450 --> 00:06:16.510
enough of the picture.

00:06:16.510 --> 00:06:18.940
And now what we're going to
do, is introduced boron.

00:06:18.940 --> 00:06:22.590
And boron goes into the
silicon lattice

00:06:22.590 --> 00:06:24.300
and covalently bonds.

00:06:24.300 --> 00:06:27.950
It doesn't go sit in some void
space in between the silicons.

00:06:27.950 --> 00:06:30.900
It actually sits on
a silicon site and

00:06:30.900 --> 00:06:32.990
substitutes for the silicon.

00:06:32.990 --> 00:06:34.390
Now, boron is group 13.

00:06:34.390 --> 00:06:36.400
It's got 3 valence electrons.

00:06:36.400 --> 00:06:40.920
And so it forms bonds
with 3 silicons.

00:06:40.920 --> 00:06:44.480
And now there's a fourth silicon
here, and that silicon

00:06:44.480 --> 00:06:46.890
has an electron, but
the boron doesn't

00:06:46.890 --> 00:06:48.270
have a fourth electron.

00:06:48.270 --> 00:06:50.150
Here's where it gets
interesting.

00:06:50.150 --> 00:06:54.900
The driving force to complete
the picture here is so great

00:06:54.900 --> 00:06:58.840
that the system will actually
pull an electron out of a

00:06:58.840 --> 00:07:00.340
silicon-silicon bond--

00:07:04.410 --> 00:07:07.420
and so I'm going to use a
different color chalk, and I'm

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:10.370
going to indicate, just for
argument's sake, that we're

00:07:10.370 --> 00:07:14.170
going to pull an electron out of
this bond here, break this

00:07:14.170 --> 00:07:17.490
bond, and shoot that electron
over to here.

00:07:17.490 --> 00:07:21.450
That way, we get r months
around the boron.

00:07:21.450 --> 00:07:23.220
It says p3 hybridized.

00:07:23.220 --> 00:07:25.100
It just doesn't have that
extra electron.

00:07:25.100 --> 00:07:27.510
But now it rips the electron
out of this

00:07:27.510 --> 00:07:29.120
silicon-silicon bond.

00:07:29.120 --> 00:07:31.640
And what's the consequence
of breaking this bod?

00:07:31.640 --> 00:07:34.770
What's the electrical feature
that we've created here?

00:07:34.770 --> 00:07:35.790
A hole.

00:07:35.790 --> 00:07:40.300
So now we've created a hole
somewhere else in the crystal

00:07:40.300 --> 00:07:43.400
in order to satisfy the
desire of boron to

00:07:43.400 --> 00:07:45.330
get that fourth bond.

00:07:45.330 --> 00:07:48.370
And now can you see that for
every boron that I introduced

00:07:48.370 --> 00:07:51.060
into the crystal, I'm
going to make a hole

00:07:51.060 --> 00:07:53.640
somewhere in the crystal.

00:07:53.640 --> 00:07:56.080
And on the energy level
diagram, where

00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:58.330
do those holes live?

00:07:58.330 --> 00:08:01.080
Those holes live in
the valence band.

00:08:01.080 --> 00:08:03.750
So let's go make the energy
level diagram.

00:08:03.750 --> 00:08:06.520
So up here we have the
conduction band, and

00:08:06.520 --> 00:08:10.220
downstairs, we have the valence
band, as before.

00:08:10.220 --> 00:08:12.520
And I'm going to assume that we
got the thermal promotion.

00:08:12.520 --> 00:08:16.220
But it's so tiny in comparison
to the amount of boron we're

00:08:16.220 --> 00:08:16.760
going to put in.

00:08:16.760 --> 00:08:19.150
I'm not going to muddy the
water here and show that

00:08:19.150 --> 00:08:21.340
you've got pair formation.

00:08:21.340 --> 00:08:24.720
Because the extent of it is so
small, it doesn't make any

00:08:24.720 --> 00:08:25.540
difference.

00:08:25.540 --> 00:08:26.850
So now what happens?

00:08:26.850 --> 00:08:29.010
Now, I know I'm going to
generate holes here, and I've

00:08:29.010 --> 00:08:30.980
got to show this energy level.

00:08:30.980 --> 00:08:33.090
And this bonding level
is different from

00:08:33.090 --> 00:08:34.060
this bonding level.

00:08:34.060 --> 00:08:34.810
Agree?

00:08:34.810 --> 00:08:38.440
Silicon-silicon bond has
different bond energy from

00:08:38.440 --> 00:08:40.460
boron-silicon bond.

00:08:40.460 --> 00:08:42.500
So that means the top
of the valence band

00:08:42.500 --> 00:08:43.810
is different from--

00:08:43.810 --> 00:08:46.920
because this valence band is
silicon-silicon-silicon.

00:08:46.920 --> 00:08:52.150
So it turns out that, and this
is not to scale, that the

00:08:52.150 --> 00:08:56.330
energy level of this bond is
just a little bit higher.

00:08:56.330 --> 00:09:02.170
And this is an energy level that
involves the accepting of

00:09:02.170 --> 00:09:05.000
electrons, whereas in
the other case, we

00:09:05.000 --> 00:09:06.900
were donating electrons.

00:09:06.900 --> 00:09:08.760
Hence, that's called
the donor level.

00:09:08.760 --> 00:09:10.780
This is called the
acceptor level.

00:09:16.860 --> 00:09:20.530
And it's about 1/50 of an
electron volt above the top of

00:09:20.530 --> 00:09:21.670
the valence band.

00:09:21.670 --> 00:09:26.020
And so what happens is that in
order to make this bond, we

00:09:26.020 --> 00:09:31.630
move something out of the
valence band up into the

00:09:31.630 --> 00:09:35.410
acceptor level and
generate a hole.

00:09:35.410 --> 00:09:38.930
And so for every boron that
we put in, we have

00:09:38.930 --> 00:09:41.080
another broken bond.

00:09:41.080 --> 00:09:43.900
And all of these lie at the same
level, but the dilution

00:09:43.900 --> 00:09:46.720
is so high, that they're so
far apart, that they don't

00:09:46.720 --> 00:09:49.080
violate the polyexplosion
principle.

00:09:49.080 --> 00:09:51.410
They're thermally promoted
up, and away we go.

00:09:51.410 --> 00:09:55.640
So now, under these
circumstances, the number of

00:09:55.640 --> 00:09:57.930
negative charge carriers no
longer equals the number of

00:09:57.930 --> 00:10:00.600
positive charge carriers.

00:10:00.600 --> 00:10:03.140
Because I've got all these
positive charge carriers.

00:10:03.140 --> 00:10:06.990
Thanks to the introduction of
boron, p is greater than n.

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:13.820
So we've made a p-type
semiconductor, by the

00:10:13.820 --> 00:10:17.390
introduction of a subvalent
impurity.

00:10:17.390 --> 00:10:21.520
And we can redo the entire
central part of last day's

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:24.850
lesson, which was
the Bohr model.

00:10:24.850 --> 00:10:26.860
Now, this is the sexiest
part of the Bohr

00:10:26.860 --> 00:10:28.450
model I've ever seen.

00:10:28.450 --> 00:10:30.750
This is really, really cool.

00:10:30.750 --> 00:10:32.840
The hole is mobile!

00:10:32.840 --> 00:10:34.620
The hole is mobile!

00:10:34.620 --> 00:10:41.980
And the boron is a little bit
shy of protons, right?

00:10:41.980 --> 00:10:45.620
It's 3 in a land of 4.

00:10:45.620 --> 00:10:47.580
So it's negative.

00:10:47.580 --> 00:10:57.000
So I've got a stationary
negative center, and I've got

00:10:57.000 --> 00:11:00.340
something positive revolving
around a negative center.

00:11:00.340 --> 00:11:03.670
This is an inverse Bohr model!

00:11:03.670 --> 00:11:07.140
Because the Bohr model has a
honking big positive center

00:11:07.140 --> 00:11:10.340
with a dinky little electron
revolving around.

00:11:10.340 --> 00:11:13.660
We've got the immobile negative
center, and the

00:11:13.660 --> 00:11:16.810
mobile hole revolving around.

00:11:16.810 --> 00:11:19.340
Go through, you get the
same set of quantum--

00:11:19.340 --> 00:11:21.600
I mean, there's a whole bunch
of quantum levels in here.

00:11:21.600 --> 00:11:22.940
Fantastic!

00:11:22.940 --> 00:11:25.200
How far that Bohr model
can take us.

00:11:25.200 --> 00:11:28.130
So now you know how to make a
p-type semiconductor, you know

00:11:28.130 --> 00:11:30.100
how to make an n-type
semiconductor.

00:11:30.100 --> 00:11:34.830
And then what you can do
is put them together.

00:11:34.830 --> 00:11:41.190
And you can put, say,
boron-doped silicon opposite

00:11:41.190 --> 00:11:44.310
phosphorus-doped silicon.

00:11:44.310 --> 00:11:46.050
Be careful here.

00:11:46.050 --> 00:11:48.680
The fonts are really critical.

00:11:48.680 --> 00:11:51.530
This is uppercase P,
for phosphorus.

00:11:51.530 --> 00:11:56.090
This is lowercase p, for
positive doping.

00:11:56.090 --> 00:11:58.190
So don't go, oh, P, phosphorus,

00:11:58.190 --> 00:11:59.450
that means it's p-type.

00:11:59.450 --> 00:12:01.970
No, P gives you extra
electrons.

00:12:01.970 --> 00:12:03.360
It's n-type.

00:12:03.360 --> 00:12:04.980
So that's what uppercase P.

00:12:04.980 --> 00:12:06.720
This is a lowercase p.

00:12:06.720 --> 00:12:09.450
This is p-type.

00:12:09.450 --> 00:12:11.820
So now I've got p-type,
n-type, and so

00:12:11.820 --> 00:12:13.020
what do I have here?

00:12:13.020 --> 00:12:17.600
I've got a p-n junction.

00:12:17.600 --> 00:12:21.750
And this is the beginning
of solid state devices,

00:12:21.750 --> 00:12:25.810
rectification of A/C current,
diodes, you name it.

00:12:25.810 --> 00:12:30.960
And it all starts with
this, the chemistry.

00:12:30.960 --> 00:12:37.290
This is the birth of the
transistor, and all the modern

00:12:37.290 --> 00:12:39.980
electronics that we have
based on that.

00:12:39.980 --> 00:12:43.735
Later on, we'll show you how you
get the boron in, and how

00:12:43.735 --> 00:12:44.940
you get the phosphorus in.

00:12:44.940 --> 00:12:47.130
You don't just come in and
sprinkle it on top, and hope

00:12:47.130 --> 00:12:48.920
that it goes to the
lattice site.

00:12:48.920 --> 00:12:51.110
There's a lot of processing
involved.

00:12:51.110 --> 00:12:51.740
OK.

00:12:51.740 --> 00:12:57.670
So this is where I want to
hold for the unit on

00:12:57.670 --> 00:13:00.910
semiconductors, and how
it fits into the

00:13:00.910 --> 00:13:02.190
grand scheme of things.

00:13:02.190 --> 00:13:04.790
So in the books, you'll see--

00:13:04.790 --> 00:13:08.020
this is a very crude drawing,
because this is showing n-type

00:13:08.020 --> 00:13:14.410
semiconductor with grossly
exaggerated numbers of donor

00:13:14.410 --> 00:13:15.540
electronics up here.

00:13:15.540 --> 00:13:17.350
There's no mention of
the donor level.

00:13:17.350 --> 00:13:19.420
So this is sort of

00:13:19.420 --> 00:13:23.390
semiconductivity, sort of pre-3091.

00:13:23.390 --> 00:13:27.900
This is extrinsic semiconduction
for idiots, I

00:13:27.900 --> 00:13:28.960
guess you'd call it.

00:13:28.960 --> 00:13:29.910
And then, same thing here.

00:13:29.910 --> 00:13:32.550
You see all of the holes
in the valence band.

00:13:32.550 --> 00:13:34.800
We know better, because we know
there's an acceptor level

00:13:34.800 --> 00:13:36.340
and there's a donor level.

00:13:36.340 --> 00:13:36.990
OK.

00:13:36.990 --> 00:13:38.850
So now we're going
to switch gears.

00:13:38.850 --> 00:13:41.390
Now here's the big transition,
right now.

00:13:41.390 --> 00:13:44.600
If the last two lectures didn't
leave high school

00:13:44.600 --> 00:13:47.090
behind, today we leave
high school behind.

00:13:47.090 --> 00:13:50.090
So those of you who have been
coasting up until now, thanks

00:13:50.090 --> 00:13:53.230
to your very good high
school background,

00:13:53.230 --> 00:13:54.390
start paying attention.

00:13:54.390 --> 00:13:56.700
Because it's high
school no more.

00:13:56.700 --> 00:13:58.790
So just to remind you
where we've come.

00:13:58.790 --> 00:14:03.630
We started over here, at the
beginning of the semester.

00:14:03.630 --> 00:14:06.980
And the big theme is going to
be, electronic structure

00:14:06.980 --> 00:14:09.530
informs bonding, which informs
state of aggregation.

00:14:09.530 --> 00:14:12.890
State of aggregation is
solid, liquid, or gas.

00:14:12.890 --> 00:14:15.330
So I want to show you how
we get to where we are.

00:14:15.330 --> 00:14:17.300
So we did all of these
topics, right?

00:14:17.300 --> 00:14:20.980
Bohr, or Sommerfeld quantum
numbers, multielectron.

00:14:20.980 --> 00:14:23.110
And then we came to
octet stability.

00:14:23.110 --> 00:14:25.430
And with octet stability,
we went a long way.

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:26.980
We got into ionic bonding.

00:14:26.980 --> 00:14:32.300
We got into completing
the valence shell.

00:14:32.300 --> 00:14:34.270
And in fact, all of this
is a consequence

00:14:34.270 --> 00:14:36.060
of the octet stability.

00:14:36.060 --> 00:14:37.430
And that led us into
the various

00:14:37.430 --> 00:14:38.610
types of primary bonding.

00:14:38.610 --> 00:14:40.720
Ionic, covalent, metallic.

00:14:40.720 --> 00:14:42.510
And in some instances,
van der Waals.

00:14:42.510 --> 00:14:44.940
Solid argon is van
der Waals bond.

00:14:44.940 --> 00:14:47.840
It's the only kind of bonding,
so it's the primary bonding.

00:14:47.840 --> 00:14:51.980
But in some cases, like HCl,
how do you get liquid HCl?

00:14:51.980 --> 00:14:54.290
How do you get solid methane?

00:14:54.290 --> 00:14:56.690
So we had invoke secondary
bonding for some of these

00:14:56.690 --> 00:14:59.880
covalent molecules, and that
invoked dipole-dipole

00:14:59.880 --> 00:15:02.150
interaction, the London
dispersion force, which is the

00:15:02.150 --> 00:15:04.710
same as the van der Walls bond,
but I decided to mix

00:15:04.710 --> 00:15:07.650
things up, so that both men get
a little bit of attention,

00:15:07.650 --> 00:15:09.290
none of them feel slighted.

00:15:09.290 --> 00:15:12.700
And finally, hydrogen bonding,
in those special instances.

00:15:12.700 --> 00:15:15.480
And that allowed us to then
determine whether something

00:15:15.480 --> 00:15:17.700
was a gas, a liquid,
or a solid.

00:15:17.700 --> 00:15:19.140
And when it's a solid,
we're happy.

00:15:19.140 --> 00:15:21.320
Because this is 3091,
and we're interested

00:15:21.320 --> 00:15:23.910
in the solid state.

00:15:23.910 --> 00:15:25.280
By the way, what is a solid?

00:15:25.280 --> 00:15:27.420
Well, here's an operative
definition.

00:15:27.420 --> 00:15:30.210
That which is dimensionally
stable, has a

00:15:30.210 --> 00:15:31.620
volume of its own.

00:15:31.620 --> 00:15:34.370
It doesn't distort in
a gravity field.

00:15:34.370 --> 00:15:35.750
All right?

00:15:35.750 --> 00:15:37.880
Liquids will distort.

00:15:37.880 --> 00:15:40.490
Fluids, gases will distort.

00:15:40.490 --> 00:15:42.870
Now, there's two ways of
classifying solids.

00:15:42.870 --> 00:15:43.900
One is bonding type.

00:15:43.900 --> 00:15:45.310
That's what we did here.

00:15:45.310 --> 00:15:47.860
But the second way of
classifying solids is based on

00:15:47.860 --> 00:15:49.355
atomic arrangements.

00:15:49.355 --> 00:15:50.150
All right?

00:15:50.150 --> 00:15:51.910
So let's look at that.

00:15:51.910 --> 00:15:54.550
There's only two types of
atomic arrangement.

00:15:54.550 --> 00:15:57.820
Ordered and disordered.

00:15:57.820 --> 00:16:00.670
I love these taxonomies
that split everything

00:16:00.670 --> 00:16:02.160
into a choice of 2.

00:16:02.160 --> 00:16:04.790
That way, you just sort of go
through life and decide, is it

00:16:04.790 --> 00:16:05.900
left or is it right?

00:16:05.900 --> 00:16:07.650
Is it up or is it down?

00:16:07.650 --> 00:16:10.150
Is it ordered or is
it disordered?

00:16:10.150 --> 00:16:11.380
So what are the characteristics

00:16:11.380 --> 00:16:12.510
or an ordered solid?

00:16:12.510 --> 00:16:15.100
It has a regular atomic
arrangement.

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:17.680
That means it's got a
long-range order.

00:16:17.680 --> 00:16:21.710
And I'll show you that in an
ordered solid, I know not only

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:24.690
where my next nearest neighbor
is, where my tenth nearest

00:16:24.690 --> 00:16:25.100
neighbor is.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:27.690
I know where my hundred and
fifty second nearest neighbor

00:16:27.690 --> 00:16:30.350
is, because it's an
ordered solid.

00:16:30.350 --> 00:16:32.720
And we have a simple Anglo-Saxon
word for an

00:16:32.720 --> 00:16:33.590
ordered solid.

00:16:33.590 --> 00:16:35.710
It's called crystal.

00:16:35.710 --> 00:16:38.460
So when I say something is a
metallic crystal, I don't mean

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:41.510
it's something that's got
magical properties, and if I

00:16:41.510 --> 00:16:44.600
put it over my head, I get
powerful or something.

00:16:44.600 --> 00:16:48.080
It just means I've got atoms
in an atomic regular

00:16:48.080 --> 00:16:49.540
arrangement.

00:16:49.540 --> 00:16:53.190
Now contrasting to that
is a disordered solid.

00:16:53.190 --> 00:16:57.010
And in that case, we have
a random arrangement.

00:16:57.010 --> 00:16:59.980
But I put an asterisk here
because, as they say in

00:16:59.980 --> 00:17:02.610
California, it's not
totally random.

00:17:02.610 --> 00:17:04.460
It's only random
up to a point.

00:17:04.460 --> 00:17:06.470
No long-range order.

00:17:06.470 --> 00:17:07.930
There may be short-range
order.

00:17:07.930 --> 00:17:11.050
In other words, I know what my
next nearest neighbor is, but

00:17:11.050 --> 00:17:14.550
I probably don't know where my
tenth nearest neighbor is

00:17:14.550 --> 00:17:18.850
Because the coordination shell
is established, but the next

00:17:18.850 --> 00:17:21.420
coordination shell, and the
next coordination shell,

00:17:21.420 --> 00:17:22.410
they're not established.

00:17:22.410 --> 00:17:25.590
And I'm going to show you, with
examples, what that means

00:17:25.590 --> 00:17:29.160
So we call those kinds of
disordered solids amorphous

00:17:29.160 --> 00:17:32.100
solids, as opposed to the
regular solids, which are

00:17:32.100 --> 00:17:33.380
crystalline solids.

00:17:33.380 --> 00:17:35.580
And there's a plain Anglo-Saxon
word for a

00:17:35.580 --> 00:17:36.790
disordered solid.

00:17:36.790 --> 00:17:38.910
It's glass.

00:17:38.910 --> 00:17:42.380
Now you might think, well, gee,
doesn't glass mean that

00:17:42.380 --> 00:17:45.230
it's transparent in
visible light?

00:17:45.230 --> 00:17:47.330
No, no.

00:17:47.330 --> 00:17:50.540
Maybe up until now, but I want
everybody who's ever taken

00:17:50.540 --> 00:17:54.660
3091 from me to be disabused of
the notion that glass means

00:17:54.660 --> 00:17:55.620
transparent.

00:17:55.620 --> 00:17:58.260
How do we think about the
question of transparency?

00:17:58.260 --> 00:18:02.990
And here I mean transparency
vis-a-vis visible light.

00:18:02.990 --> 00:18:04.830
I'm not going to say, what's
transparent to x-rays?

00:18:04.830 --> 00:18:06.560
That's pedantry.

00:18:06.560 --> 00:18:09.310
So how do we think about
whether something is

00:18:09.310 --> 00:18:11.430
transparent to visible light?

00:18:11.430 --> 00:18:14.230
We just ask ourselves, is the
band gap greater than 3

00:18:14.230 --> 00:18:16.090
electron volts?

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:19.210
The band gap is greater than 3
electron volts, visible light

00:18:19.210 --> 00:18:20.185
zooms right through.

00:18:20.185 --> 00:18:23.430
It doesn't have enough energy
to excite the electrons, be

00:18:23.430 --> 00:18:24.780
absorbed, and re-emit.

00:18:24.780 --> 00:18:26.980
So that's what transparency
means.

00:18:26.980 --> 00:18:32.130
So I can have the kind of
material that's used in things

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:33.820
like eyeglasses.

00:18:33.820 --> 00:18:36.300
It's transparent to visible
light because of

00:18:36.300 --> 00:18:37.940
its high band gap.

00:18:37.940 --> 00:18:41.390
Diamond, diamond is transparent
to visible light,

00:18:41.390 --> 00:18:43.950
and you wouldn't dare insult
diamond by saying

00:18:43.950 --> 00:18:45.700
that diamond is glass!

00:18:45.700 --> 00:18:48.030
In fact, watch the old gangster
movies from the

00:18:48.030 --> 00:18:52.790
1930s, that was the derogatory
term for fake diamonds.

00:18:52.790 --> 00:18:55.270
You call them glass.

00:18:55.270 --> 00:18:58.340
So how is it that diamond, which
is crystalline, it's

00:18:58.340 --> 00:19:01.850
transparent to visible light,
and yet the window glass that

00:19:01.850 --> 00:19:04.740
we have is transparent
to visible light?

00:19:04.740 --> 00:19:07.800
It has nothing to do with
state of order.

00:19:07.800 --> 00:19:09.100
Has everything to
do with this.

00:19:09.100 --> 00:19:12.650
In fact, David, if we could
shoot to the document camera,

00:19:12.650 --> 00:19:15.700
I'll show you a piece of glass
that's not transparent to

00:19:15.700 --> 00:19:17.340
visible light.

00:19:17.340 --> 00:19:19.240
How do we zoom in
on this thing?

00:19:19.240 --> 00:19:20.890
OK.

00:19:20.890 --> 00:19:21.460
Auto focus.

00:19:21.460 --> 00:19:23.530
So what I'm showing you is
a piece of obsidian.

00:19:28.160 --> 00:19:30.320
It's a naturally occurring
mineral.

00:19:30.320 --> 00:19:34.680
It's rich in silica, and it's
turned dark because it's got

00:19:34.680 --> 00:19:37.810
some iron impurity, and the iron
absorbs in the visible.

00:19:37.810 --> 00:19:41.050
And this is clearly not
transparent to visible light,

00:19:41.050 --> 00:19:42.760
and yet, it is a disordered
solid.

00:19:42.760 --> 00:19:44.510
This is a glassy solid.

00:19:44.510 --> 00:19:48.920
In fact, the white
speckles there

00:19:48.920 --> 00:19:51.730
are devitrified obsidian.

00:19:51.730 --> 00:19:54.440
It's actually started
to crystallize.

00:19:54.440 --> 00:19:58.040
So the crystalline form is the
part that's transparent.

00:19:58.040 --> 00:20:00.220
If you could peel off this
crystalline form, you'd

00:20:00.220 --> 00:20:01.370
actually end up with
something that's

00:20:01.370 --> 00:20:02.430
transparent to visible light.

00:20:02.430 --> 00:20:04.920
So here's an example of where
the crystalline form is

00:20:04.920 --> 00:20:07.930
transparent to visible light,
and the glassy form is opaque.

00:20:07.930 --> 00:20:11.240
So glass has nothing to
do with transparency.

00:20:11.240 --> 00:20:15.290
This is how you think about the
question of transparency.

