00:24:56.440 --> 00:24:58.990
These are some giant crystals
I didn't dare drag in.

00:24:58.990 --> 00:25:01.050
This is sort of human-sized
scale.

00:25:01.050 --> 00:25:04.190
This is balsalt, which is a
magnesium iron silicate.

00:25:04.190 --> 00:25:07.170
It's on a coast of Iceland.

00:25:07.170 --> 00:25:10.180
Dave, let's show them
a few more.

00:25:10.180 --> 00:25:12.180
Here's one more, if we go
to the document camera.

00:25:12.180 --> 00:25:14.680
This was beryllium aluminum
silicate.

00:25:14.680 --> 00:25:16.910
This is a barrel.

00:25:16.910 --> 00:25:20.215
And you can see, this has
got a hexagonal habit.

00:25:23.400 --> 00:25:26.780
So something's going on at the
atomic level that's different

00:25:26.780 --> 00:25:29.360
as we go from one crystal
structure to the other.

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:30.250
What else have I got here?

00:25:30.250 --> 00:25:33.320
Here's some calcite, here's
some fluorite.

00:25:33.320 --> 00:25:34.410
Look at this one.

00:25:34.410 --> 00:25:39.420
This is square pyramidal
but it's ionic.

00:25:39.420 --> 00:25:43.190
So don't give me any of
