00:25:52.840 --> 00:25:56.570
So then we jump to
1781, to France.

00:25:56.570 --> 00:26:01.100
Rene Juste-Hauy was at the
Sorbonne, and he was studying

00:26:01.100 --> 00:26:02.900
the cleavage of calcite
crystals.

00:26:02.900 --> 00:26:04.890
In other words, he was
taking these things

00:26:04.890 --> 00:26:05.670
and breaking them.

00:26:05.670 --> 00:26:08.040
So he'd go to work every
day and break things.

00:26:08.040 --> 00:26:11.710
And he studied the shards, and
he found that the shards were

00:26:11.710 --> 00:26:13.300
all rhombahedral.

00:26:13.300 --> 00:26:15.150
the same shape as the
parent crystal.

00:26:15.150 --> 00:26:17.070
No matter how small the
shards got, they

00:26:17.070 --> 00:26:18.650
always looked like this.

00:26:18.650 --> 00:26:20.580
He didn't end up with
cubic shards.

00:26:20.580 --> 00:26:22.245
He didn't end up with
long slivers.

00:26:22.245 --> 00:26:25.830
He always ended up with
rhombahedral slices.

00:26:25.830 --> 00:26:29.960
So the other thing is that he
didn't end up with any voids.

00:26:29.960 --> 00:26:32.790
No matter how he cut this thing,
he never got voids.

00:26:32.790 --> 00:26:36.740
So he reasoned that this must be
the way things are packing

00:26:36.740 --> 00:26:40.330
in three space perfectly.

00:26:40.330 --> 00:26:42.100
So then he said, gee.

00:26:42.100 --> 00:26:44.540
If they pack perfectly
rhombahedrally--

00:26:44.540 --> 00:26:48.370
we all know that we can stack
boxes together perfectly,

00:26:48.370 --> 00:26:49.510
cubes together.

00:26:49.510 --> 00:26:53.100
So he, being a Frenchman, said,
what's the mathematical

00:26:53.100 --> 00:26:54.160
formulation?

00:26:54.160 --> 00:26:56.280
They were steeped in
mathematics there.

00:26:56.280 --> 00:26:58.320
That wasn't a slur against
the French.

00:26:58.320 --> 00:26:59.300
It's a compliment.

00:26:59.300 --> 00:27:03.720
He said, what are the
mathematically distinct

00:27:03.720 --> 00:27:07.370
shapes, that if we stack them
together in three space they

00:27:07.370 --> 00:27:09.800
will fill three space
with no void?

00:27:09.800 --> 00:27:11.370
And the answer is seven.

00:27:11.370 --> 00:27:13.870
Seven space-filling
volume elements.

00:27:13.870 --> 00:27:17.890
By the way, the gabled milk
carton isn't one of them.

00:27:17.890 --> 00:27:20.850
And so he called the crystal
system, so I call seven

00:27:20.850 --> 00:27:24.050
distinct shades of
milk cartons.

00:27:24.050 --> 00:27:26.850
And these are the seven crystal
systems, and they're

00:27:26.850 --> 00:27:29.680
described geometrically, and
you'll get a chance to go

00:27:29.680 --> 00:27:30.010
through them.

00:27:30.010 --> 00:27:30.940
The cube is one of them.

00:27:30.940 --> 00:27:31.690
Tetragonal.

00:27:31.690 --> 00:27:34.850
Here's the calcite,
rhombahedral.

00:27:34.850 --> 00:27:36.725
There's barrel, hexagonal,
and so on.

00:27:36.725 --> 00:27:40.510
The seven different ways you
can feel three space.

00:27:40.510 --> 00:27:43.680
And this is from the archival
readings of my predecessor,

00:27:43.680 --> 00:27:46.080
Professor Witt.

00:27:46.080 --> 00:27:47.680
Actually, just to give your
a sense, here's the

00:27:47.680 --> 00:27:48.940
two-dimensional analogy.

00:27:48.940 --> 00:27:52.190
If I said to you, we're going
to open a company, and we're

00:27:52.190 --> 00:27:54.890
going to make bathroom tile, and
we want to make it sort of

00:27:54.890 --> 00:27:58.840
an upscale company, you know,
not everybody wants boring old

00:27:58.840 --> 00:28:00.160
square tiles.

00:28:00.160 --> 00:28:03.910
But definitely, I can cover two
space with square tiles by

00:28:03.910 --> 00:28:06.540
putting them side by side,
one on top of the other.

00:28:06.540 --> 00:28:08.180
What's another way I can fill?

00:28:08.180 --> 00:28:09.800
I can go with rectangular
tiles.

00:28:09.800 --> 00:28:12.210
So this dimension is different
from that dimension.

00:28:12.210 --> 00:28:12.970
What's another way?

00:28:12.970 --> 00:28:17.770
I can use a rhombus, right,
at 60 degrees.

00:28:17.770 --> 00:28:22.540
Or I can use just a plain old
parallelepipede at some

00:28:22.540 --> 00:28:23.620
arbitrary angle.

00:28:23.620 --> 00:28:26.550
And if you go over to the Stata
Center, to the Gehry

00:28:26.550 --> 00:28:29.400
building, take a look at
the shape that they

00:28:29.400 --> 00:28:31.850
chose as the unit cell.

00:28:31.850 --> 00:28:35.870
This is the repeat group, if
you like, or the unit cell,

00:28:35.870 --> 00:28:37.770
because that's the one that's
going to be cookie cutter

00:28:37.770 --> 00:28:39.660
replicated, side by side.

00:28:39.660 --> 00:28:42.470
When you're putting the skin
on a building, you have to

00:28:42.470 --> 00:28:44.830
make everything fit with
no holidays, right?

00:28:44.830 --> 00:28:46.810
Because you don't want gaps.

00:28:46.810 --> 00:28:54.340
what they chose was
this area element.

00:28:54.340 --> 00:28:56.680
And all the pieces of stainless
steel are cut to

00:28:56.680 --> 00:28:57.670
this shape.

00:28:57.670 --> 00:28:59.340
And that's how you
make things fit.

00:28:59.340 --> 00:29:02.510
How you take something and make
it fit around a three

00:29:02.510 --> 00:29:04.160
dimensional object is tricky.

00:29:04.160 --> 00:29:06.270
It's the same thing as the
clothing problem, right?

00:29:06.270 --> 00:29:08.510
How do you take a flat piece of
cloth and make it fit the

00:29:08.510 --> 00:29:11.100
contour of the human body?

00:29:11.100 --> 00:29:13.750
At least, you know, in men's
clothes, you know, we've got

00:29:13.750 --> 00:29:14.220
dimensions.

00:29:14.220 --> 00:29:18.540
We've got sleeve length, got
waist, chest. We've got all

00:29:18.540 --> 00:29:19.110
these numbers.

00:29:19.110 --> 00:29:20.890
For a woman, 8.

00:29:20.890 --> 00:29:22.920
One number?

00:29:22.920 --> 00:29:24.070
One number?

00:29:24.070 --> 00:29:27.572
Fashion designers don't
know crystallograpy!

00:29:27.572 --> 00:29:29.700
If they knew crystallography,
they'd know how

00:29:29.700 --> 00:29:31.480
to specify the shapes!

00:29:31.480 --> 00:29:33.860
If you understand this, you can
start your own business

00:29:33.860 --> 00:29:34.950
and make clothes that fit.

00:29:34.950 --> 00:29:37.310
And I guarantee you, there's
a market out there for

00:29:37.310 --> 00:29:39.420
clothes that fit.

00:29:39.420 --> 00:29:41.560
What about this one?

00:29:41.560 --> 00:29:42.320
Pentagon.

00:29:42.320 --> 00:29:44.820
We're going to make pentagonal
bathroom tile.

00:29:44.820 --> 00:29:48.560
Well, when we install these,
we're going to have to use two

00:29:48.560 --> 00:29:49.170
different colors.

00:29:49.170 --> 00:29:51.050
You can see this
up here, right?

00:29:51.050 --> 00:29:53.390
This is pentagonal
bathroom tile.

00:29:53.390 --> 00:29:53.970
It doesn't fit.

00:29:53.970 --> 00:29:55.960
You've got all these
white spots.

00:29:55.960 --> 00:29:57.550
So this is not a unit cell.

00:29:57.550 --> 00:30:01.900
This is not one of the crystal
systems for two dimensional.

00:30:01.900 --> 00:30:02.850
So this one's no good.

00:30:02.850 --> 00:30:05.370
We better put an x through it,
in case someone fell asleep,

00:30:05.370 --> 00:30:09.100
and wake up, and then tell
me that that's OK.

00:30:09.100 --> 00:30:09.540
All right.

00:30:09.540 --> 00:30:14.400
So then we move about half
a century forward, to the

00:30:14.400 --> 00:30:18.560
turbulent year 1848,
also in France.

00:30:18.560 --> 00:30:20.300
Auguste Bravais.

00:30:20.300 --> 00:30:21.970
And what Bravais did, is
he said, all right.

00:30:21.970 --> 00:30:24.120
This is just filling space.

00:30:24.120 --> 00:30:25.320
But where are the atoms?

00:30:25.320 --> 00:30:27.310
I haven't told you where
the atoms are, right?

00:30:27.310 --> 00:30:29.430
You know, as far as you're
concerned, maybe there's one

00:30:29.430 --> 00:30:32.270
atom in each of these boxes.

00:30:32.270 --> 00:30:34.890
Or maybe there's atoms at
the corners of the box.

00:30:34.890 --> 00:30:36.410
Or maybe there's atoms
at the corner and the

00:30:36.410 --> 00:30:37.080
center of the box.

00:30:37.080 --> 00:30:38.120
Where are the atoms?

00:30:38.120 --> 00:30:40.700
I've simply told you that I
can fill three space with

00:30:40.700 --> 00:30:44.350
boxes, or with these rectangular
boxes, and so on.

00:30:44.350 --> 00:30:48.470
So he set out mathematically
to prove how many different

00:30:48.470 --> 00:30:51.500
arrangements of points
there are in space.

00:30:51.500 --> 00:30:53.640
It's sort of like saying, if I
want to tell you where all the

00:30:53.640 --> 00:30:55.930
apples are in the orchard, I'm
going to tell you where the

00:30:55.930 --> 00:30:57.850
trees are, and I'm going
to tell you where the

00:30:57.850 --> 00:30:59.370
apples are on a tree.

00:30:59.370 --> 00:31:04.120
So where do the atoms go
inside these boxes?

00:31:04.120 --> 00:31:09.130
Turns out there's 14 different
arrangements.

00:31:09.130 --> 00:31:10.140
And what do I mean by that?

00:31:10.140 --> 00:31:11.190
This is a good example.

00:31:11.190 --> 00:31:14.980
So we've already established
that the cube is a

00:31:14.980 --> 00:31:16.690
space-filling volume element.

00:31:16.690 --> 00:31:18.020
It's one of the seven.

00:31:18.020 --> 00:31:18.850
But look.

00:31:18.850 --> 00:31:22.660
If I'm one of the atoms at the
corners here, I've got six

00:31:22.660 --> 00:31:24.350
nearest neighbors.

00:31:24.350 --> 00:31:27.780
This is also a cube, but it's
got atoms at the corners and

00:31:27.780 --> 00:31:28.610
an atom in the center.

00:31:28.610 --> 00:31:30.130
You might say, well, what's
the big deal?

00:31:30.130 --> 00:31:33.220
If you're in the atom in the
center, and you look to the

00:31:33.220 --> 00:31:36.020
nearest neighbors, you've got
eight nearest neighbors.

00:31:36.020 --> 00:31:38.190
Here you only have six
nearest neighbors.

00:31:38.190 --> 00:31:42.900
So this is spatially
differentiated from this.

00:31:42.900 --> 00:31:44.340
So what why don't
we keep going?

00:31:44.340 --> 00:31:47.410
And by the way, the same
environment of that central

00:31:47.410 --> 00:31:50.530
atom that's coded green is the
same environment of any of the

00:31:50.530 --> 00:31:51.440
atoms on the corners.

00:31:51.440 --> 00:31:53.860
They're all symmetric.

00:31:53.860 --> 00:31:57.230
So both are cubes, but they
have different space point

00:31:57.230 --> 00:31:58.240
environments.

00:31:58.240 --> 00:32:01.070
And here's a third one, where
we put atoms at the corners

00:32:01.070 --> 00:32:02.620
and atoms on each
of the faces.

00:32:02.620 --> 00:32:05.550
So this atom on the face, you
can see, it's got one, two,

00:32:05.550 --> 00:32:08.030
three, four atoms in
the plane, three

00:32:08.030 --> 00:32:08.800
behind, three in front.

00:32:08.800 --> 00:32:10.210
It's got 12 nearest neighbors.

00:32:10.210 --> 00:32:11.910
This has got eight nearest
neighbors, this has got six

00:32:11.910 --> 00:32:12.980
nearest neighbors.

00:32:12.980 --> 00:32:16.350
So Bravais went through and he
said, let's take those seven

00:32:16.350 --> 00:32:20.780
crystal systems. Let's put atoms
in distinguishable ways.

00:32:20.780 --> 00:32:24.240
How many distinguishable ways
can we come up with atom

00:32:24.240 --> 00:32:24.810
arrangements?

00:32:24.810 --> 00:32:26.345
And the answer is 14.

00:32:26.345 --> 00:32:29.130
Now, what we're going to do in
3091, is we're just going to

00:32:29.130 --> 00:32:31.570
confine our conversation
to the cubics.

00:32:31.570 --> 00:32:36.500
Because you use orthogonal
vectors, they're all the same

00:32:36.500 --> 00:32:39.010
length, the mathematics
are simple, and the

00:32:39.010 --> 00:32:40.120
principles are the same.

00:32:40.120 --> 00:32:43.200
And by the way, boatloads
of materials are

00:32:43.200 --> 00:32:44.270
in the cubic system.

00:32:44.270 --> 00:32:47.400
So it's not as though we just
chose something that's

00:32:47.400 --> 00:32:51.070
convenient but irrelevant.

00:32:51.070 --> 00:32:54.450
So here are the different
Bravais lattices.

00:32:54.450 --> 00:32:56.710
So you can see the cubic,
there's simple cubic,

00:32:56.710 --> 00:32:58.700
body-centered cubic,
face-centered cubic.

00:32:58.700 --> 00:33:01.250
With tetragonal, there
is simple tetragonal,

00:33:01.250 --> 00:33:03.100
body-centered tetragonal.

00:33:03.100 --> 00:33:04.490
There's no face-center
tetragonal.

00:33:04.490 --> 00:33:07.550
If you try to make face-center
tetragonal it's degenerate,

00:33:07.550 --> 00:33:08.980
reverts to one of the
other systems.

00:33:08.980 --> 00:33:12.450
So these are the distinguishable
systems. And

00:33:12.450 --> 00:33:15.910
everything, including
crystalline proteins--

00:33:15.910 --> 00:33:20.180
if the protein crystallizes, it
forms atomic arrangements

00:33:20.180 --> 00:33:22.300
in one of these Bravais
lattices.

00:33:22.300 --> 00:33:24.770
Everything conforms to one of
these Bravais lattices.

00:33:24.770 --> 00:33:27.760
And if it doesn't, it means it
lacks long-range order, in

00:33:27.760 --> 00:33:30.620
which case it is a glass.

00:33:30.620 --> 00:33:31.870
That's it.

00:33:34.100 --> 00:33:35.930
So here's face-centered cubic.

00:33:35.930 --> 00:33:39.280
You can see the placement.

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:42.670
But there's something that's
been simplified here.

00:33:42.670 --> 00:33:47.540
Right now what you see is a
single atom, designated by a

00:33:47.540 --> 00:33:48.470
hard sphere.

00:33:48.470 --> 00:33:52.660
But at each of these lattice
points, I can put

00:33:52.660 --> 00:33:53.550
more than one atom.

00:33:53.550 --> 00:33:55.450
So let me show you what
I mean by that.

00:33:55.450 --> 00:34:00.120
What I want to do, is put
different numbers of atom

00:34:00.120 --> 00:34:01.930
arrangements at the
lattice point.

00:34:01.930 --> 00:34:05.090
So those positions, the
distinguishable positions, are

00:34:05.090 --> 00:34:06.450
called lattice points.

00:34:06.450 --> 00:34:09.890
And now I want to define
the crystal structure--

00:34:09.890 --> 00:34:13.080
the crystal structure is the
complete accounting of atomic

00:34:13.080 --> 00:34:14.300
arrangement.

00:34:14.300 --> 00:34:20.630
It's the complete description
of atomic arrangement.

00:34:23.200 --> 00:34:25.510
And we don't have to go too far,
because we just have to

00:34:25.510 --> 00:34:27.920
get the base unit, the unit
cell, and then just

00:34:27.920 --> 00:34:28.840
repeat the unit cell.

00:34:28.840 --> 00:34:33.020
Complete description of
atomic arrangement.

00:34:33.020 --> 00:34:37.540
And so how we going
to go about this?

00:34:37.540 --> 00:34:39.250
We're going to start with
a Bravais lattice.

00:34:42.504 --> 00:34:44.140
And what is the Bravais
lattice?

00:34:44.140 --> 00:34:46.479
The Bravais lattice is simply
a point environment.

00:34:51.260 --> 00:34:53.610
And this will mean something to
you in about three minutes,

00:34:53.610 --> 00:35:00.490
when I give you the rest
of the description.

00:35:00.490 --> 00:35:09.190
So it's a set of points in
space and the basis.

00:35:09.190 --> 00:35:10.140
And what is the basis?

00:35:10.140 --> 00:35:12.740
The basis is the atom group
at each lattice point.

00:35:20.280 --> 00:35:23.260
So what do we mean by that?

00:35:23.260 --> 00:35:27.270
Well, let's look at what's
up on the board.

00:35:27.270 --> 00:35:29.800
What's up on the board is
face-centered cubic.

00:35:29.800 --> 00:35:30.810
So let's do all of these.

00:35:30.810 --> 00:35:37.440
So we're going to say that the
Bravais lattice, in this case,

00:35:37.440 --> 00:35:39.990
in face-centered cubic, FCC.

00:35:39.990 --> 00:35:42.100
That's what this one is,
up on the board.

00:35:42.100 --> 00:35:43.870
And we've got dots indicate
the points.

00:35:43.870 --> 00:35:45.130
Because really, the points
are nothing.

00:35:45.130 --> 00:35:46.080
It's a concept.

00:35:46.080 --> 00:35:46.850
See, it's French.

00:35:46.850 --> 00:35:48.430
It's a concept, right?

00:35:48.430 --> 00:35:49.930
What's this?

00:35:49.930 --> 00:35:50.760
See what I'm holding?

00:35:50.760 --> 00:35:53.100
I'm holding a Bravais lattice.

00:35:53.100 --> 00:35:54.050
It's just a set of points.

00:35:54.050 --> 00:35:58.910
It's like a John Cage piece,
you know, a bunch of rests.

00:35:58.910 --> 00:36:01.820
So if I go to the piano
and I play rests in

00:36:01.820 --> 00:36:05.050
five four time, listen.

00:36:05.050 --> 00:36:05.680
Isn't that great?

00:36:05.680 --> 00:36:07.040
Man, it's fantastic.

00:36:07.040 --> 00:36:09.660
All the different rests,
and different--

00:36:09.660 --> 00:36:12.130
So this is a set of
lattice points.

00:36:12.130 --> 00:36:14.060
Now I'm going to put
something on them.

00:36:14.060 --> 00:36:14.880
You think I'm kidding.

00:36:14.880 --> 00:36:15.640
I'm not.

00:36:15.640 --> 00:36:15.910
All right.

00:36:15.910 --> 00:36:17.160
Now what's the basis?

00:36:19.880 --> 00:36:24.455
If I put a single atom, we have
what's up on the slide.

00:36:27.600 --> 00:36:29.880
And so that's the representation
of metal.

00:36:29.880 --> 00:36:34.280
So for example, gold is FCC,
with a single gold atom at

00:36:34.280 --> 00:36:35.300
each lattice point.

00:36:35.300 --> 00:36:37.870
Aluminum, copper, platinum.

00:36:37.870 --> 00:36:39.540
These are all FCC metals.

00:36:39.540 --> 00:36:43.570
So there's a single atom at
Bravais lattice point, and so

00:36:43.570 --> 00:36:49.190
the crystal structure
is known as FCC.

00:36:49.190 --> 00:36:50.780
It's the same as the
Bravais lattice.

