00:45:35.780 --> 00:45:36.610
Well, what's the unit cell?

00:45:36.610 --> 00:45:40.190
The unit cell is this cookie
cutter cube that's the repeat

00:45:40.190 --> 00:45:44.340
unit, and it has a dimension
here called a, which is the

00:45:44.340 --> 00:45:46.985
lattice constant.

00:45:46.985 --> 00:45:49.440
It's the size of the box.

00:45:49.440 --> 00:45:51.440
So what's the volume
of the unit cell

00:45:51.440 --> 00:45:52.750
Well, duh, it's a cubed.

00:45:52.750 --> 00:45:54.100
That's obvious, all right?

00:45:54.100 --> 00:45:56.200
Doesn't matter whether it's
simple cubic, face-centered

00:45:56.200 --> 00:45:57.900
cubic, body centered cubic.

00:45:57.900 --> 00:46:00.740
How many lattice points
per unit cell?

00:46:00.740 --> 00:46:05.385
Well, that's-- how many atoms
do I get per unit cell?

00:46:05.385 --> 00:46:08.120
If you look at this, you
say, well gee, it's--

00:46:08.120 --> 00:46:09.960
you know, if you've got the
simple cubic, you've got them

00:46:09.960 --> 00:46:11.820
at the eight corners, so
it's eight, right?

00:46:11.820 --> 00:46:15.800
Well, no, because each atom on
the corner is inside this

00:46:15.800 --> 00:46:18.950
cell, but it's also inside the
neighboring cell, and it's

00:46:18.950 --> 00:46:21.200
inside each of the eight
neighboring cells.

00:46:21.200 --> 00:46:23.725
So I have eight times
one eighth.

00:46:23.725 --> 00:46:28.000
So the total amount of atom
within the cube is only one.

00:46:28.000 --> 00:46:30.110
That's why you've got to go
through this derivation.

00:46:30.110 --> 00:46:32.540
So here's an example for
face-centered cubic.

00:46:32.540 --> 00:46:35.190
You see the corners, one,
two, three, four?

00:46:35.190 --> 00:46:36.580
There's eight of those.

00:46:36.580 --> 00:46:38.300
Eight times one eighth is one.

00:46:38.300 --> 00:46:40.770
And then you've got these atoms
on the face, and there's

00:46:40.770 --> 00:46:43.130
one, two, three, four,
five, six, right?

00:46:43.130 --> 00:46:44.850
Six faces.

00:46:44.850 --> 00:46:46.870
But each of these atoms
on the face is only

00:46:46.870 --> 00:46:48.170
half inside the cube.

00:46:48.170 --> 00:46:50.420
The other half is in
the other cube.

00:46:50.420 --> 00:46:52.850
So I got six times one half is
three, and that gives me four.

00:46:52.850 --> 00:46:55.270
So that's how you go through,
and figure out

00:46:55.270 --> 00:46:55.990
what's going on.

00:46:55.990 --> 00:46:58.270
And then you can look at things
like nearest neighbor

00:46:58.270 --> 00:47:00.920
distance, and what's the
relationship between the

00:47:00.920 --> 00:47:03.860
radius, if you're looking
at hard sphere packing.

00:47:03.860 --> 00:47:04.650
So here's a good example.

00:47:04.650 --> 00:47:07.240
Here's the hard sphere
packing model.

00:47:07.240 --> 00:47:09.920
So I've got atoms all
the same size, and

00:47:09.920 --> 00:47:12.360
they're packed to touch.

00:47:12.360 --> 00:47:14.830
And they're packed to touch so
that in the end, I end up with

00:47:14.830 --> 00:47:17.000
a face centered cubic
arrangement.

00:47:17.000 --> 00:47:20.370
And so what's the relationship
between the radius and the

00:47:20.370 --> 00:47:21.370
lattice constant?

00:47:21.370 --> 00:47:23.170
And it's just simple
trigonometry, right?

00:47:23.170 --> 00:47:27.500
4r equals 2a squared, and you go
through it, and that's how

00:47:27.500 --> 00:47:30.090
you end up with all
these formulas.

00:47:30.090 --> 00:47:31.880
So that's what going on.

